              "body": [
                {
                  "created": "2026-07-17T18:57:55.301Z",
                  "creator": "lucia",
                  "purpose": "commenting",
                  "type": "TextualBody",
                  "format": "text/html",
                  "value": "<p>Reynolds’s dogs are never seen again. According to an <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW119443315 BCX2\" href=\"https://www.wmagazine.com/story/exclusive-daniel-day-lewis-giving-up-acting-phantom-thread\"><u>exclusive interview Daniel Day-Lewis granted W Magazine,</u></a> he “meticulously invented every aspect of Woodcock’s” life, “[e]ven his dogs: ‘I wanted lurchers,’ Day-Lewis said. ‘I gave so much thought to every single detail. I was probably infuriating.’” The dog pictured in the magazine’s photoshoot resembles the dogs in this scene, which audiences can only glimpse for a few seconds. <em>The Observer’s Book of Dogs</em>, briefly <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW119443315 BCX2\" href=\"https://ptannotated.com/items/phan-15235.html\"><u>pictured</u></a> later in the film, describes lurchers as follows: “Artisan-sportsmen, poachers and gipsy caravans all have a fancy for the Lurcher, who sagacity, speed and hardiness suit well the conditions of its owners. This type of dog is not a recognized pure breed, is not included on the Registers of the cynological circles. However, it is an all-purpose utility dog, usually of Greyhound or Whippet shape, which, although ostracized, is a fairly common race in the Midlands and north of England. Height about 24 in. Weight 30—50 lb. Colour black, black-and-tan, tricolour or similar mixtures. Coat short and harsh. Head long and tapering; ears small, rose or pricked; body racy; tail long and thin” (Hubbard, <em>The Observer’s Book of Dogs</em>, 180).&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>"
                }
              ],
              "target": {
                "type": "SpecificResource",
                "source": "https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01942/canvas/1",
